// Go workspace for in-repo development across zeroid's three published
// modules. When you run `go build` or `go test` from anywhere inside the
// repo, Go reads this file and treats the three modules as one workspace
// — local code in ./pkg/authjwt and ./pkg/dpop is used directly,
// regardless of what versions zeroid/go.mod's require directives
// declare. Each module's go.mod can therefore reference real published
// versions (which downstream consumers need for `go get` resolution),
// without breaking the dev experience.
//
// This replaces the older pattern of `replace github.com/highflame-ai/
// zeroid/pkg/foo => ./pkg/foo` directives in zeroid/go.mod. Those
// directives worked for in-repo dev but were invisible to downstream
// consumers (Go does not honor a transitive module's replace
// directives), so external `go get github.com/highflame-ai/zeroid@vX.Y.Z`
// always failed against the `v0.0.0` placeholder version. The workspace
// + real-version pattern is the modern Go-monorepo idiom — see
// kubernetes, etcd, opentelemetry-go for the same shape.
//
// Releases: see RELEASING.md for how the prepare-release workflow
// keeps the cross-module version refs in zeroid/go.mod in lockstep with
// the published release tag, so consumers see consistent versions
// across the root module + sub-modules.

go 1.26.0

use (
	.
	./pkg/authjwt
	./pkg/dpop
)
